---

[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'More than 40,000 companies run their entire marketing operation themselves instead of paying for HubSpot. And the way the project behind it is handling AI breaks the script. So, here\'s the backstory. Mautic is open-source marketing automation, the'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'engine behind your email campaigns, your landing pages, and your contact scoring. Everything a platform like HubSpot rolls into one paid suite. The twist is that you host Mautic yourself on your own'

[00:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'server. So, your contact records never leave your control. It started back in 2014. It\'s picked up close to 10,000 stars on GitHub. It\'s licensed under the GPL, and it\'s even certified as a'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'digital public good. It\'s built and maintained by a community of more than a thousand volunteers. And the reason it\'s back in the news is AI. Every marketing tool out there is racing to bolt a'

[00:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'chatbot straight onto your contacts. Mautic did the exact opposite. It stopped and wrote a manifesto first. Enjoying this so far? Subscribe to the YouTube channel and grab the free daily'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'newsletter at indiehacker.news. New deep dive every weekday. The repo\'s readme page tells you exactly who this project thinks it is. Right at the top, past the logo and the badges,'

[01:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there\'s a phrase they repeat on purpose that this is the most privacy-focused product in the category. Scroll down to the benefits of running your own copy, the kind of thing the page sells hard. A'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'little further, there\'s a blunt warning that installing from source is for people comfortable on the command line because this is real infrastructure, not a signup form. But keep scrolling because the bottom of the page is the'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'real surprise. The whole back half turns into a wall of contributor faces, hundreds and hundreds of people who\'ve shipped code into this over the years. &gt;&gt; So, how does this stack up against what'

[02:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'most companies actually pay for? The default in this space is HubSpot, and HubSpot is not cheap. Its professional marketing tier runs around $890 a month, and the enterprise tier sits near 3,600'

[02:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'before you\'ve added a single extra contact. Adobe owns Marketo at the high end. Salesforce has Pardot. And they all share the same shape. Your data lives on their servers, and you rent access to it'

[02:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'every single month. Mautic flips that whole arrangement. The software is free. You run it on hosting you already pay for, and there\'s no contact limit quietly bumping you into the next price tier. And here\'s the part that matters'

[02:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for where everything is going. When those platforms add AI, they\'re running it on your customer data inside their cloud. Step back and look at the footprint here.'

[02:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This project has been shipping for more than a decade. It\'s running inside tens of thousands of companies, reaching into nearly 200 countries, and the core of it costs nothing to run. Let\'s get concrete about what\'s actually'

[03:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the box, because this isn\'t a stripped-down newsletter tool. The centerpiece is a visual campaign builder, a drag-and-drop canvas where you wire up the logic of a campaign. Someone downloads a guide. You wait 2'

[03:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'days. If they opened your email, send this. If they didn\'t, branch them over here. On top of that sits a drag-and-drop email builder and a matching landing page builder, both rebuilt recently on a modern editor, so'

[03:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the people doing marketing can actually use them without a developer. Then, there\'s segmentation where you build dynamic segments out of behavior and contact fields, and people flow in and'

[03:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'out of them automatically as they act. And running underneath all of it is lead scoring, where every contact quietly racks up points based on what they do, so your sales side can see who\'s'

[03:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'genuinely warming up. Want to be featured? Pitch your open-source repo at indiehacker.news/apply and get in front of thousands of builders.'

[04:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Beyond the core, two things are worth knowing. First, this isn\'t only email. The same campaign can reach people over text messages and web push, not just the inbox, and it can even reshape the content on your own website based on'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'who\'s visiting, with no per channel surcharge. The second is how it\'s handling AI, which is where it broke from the pack. Instead of shipping some built-in assistant wired to a single vendor, the community published an AI'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'manifesto and spun up a working group to govern it. The rule they landed on goes further than you\'d expect. Mautic itself hosts no AI at all. It stays completely model agnostic, so you bring your own'

[04:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'engine, point it at whatever model you trust, and nothing about your contacts gets handed to someone else\'s cloud to make it work. The agent layer is a framework you control, not a captive chatbot.'

[05:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Under the hood, Mautic is a PHP application built on the Symfony framework with a MySQL or MariaDB database doing the heavy lifting. That choice tells you something. This thing is designed to run on completely'

[05:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ordinary, cheap web hosting, the same boring stack that runs most of the web, which is a big part of why it spread so far. The modern way to install it is through Composer, the standard PHP package'

[05:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'manager, and the repo even ships a ready-made DDEV config, so you can spin up a full local environment with a single command. The newest version modernized the whole base. It now wants'

[05:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'PHP 8.2 or newer and rides on Symphony 7, and it exposes a proper version 2 API, so you can drive the entire system from your own code.'

[05:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Installing it looks like a normal modern PHP project. You pull down the recommended project skeleton with composer, drop in your database details, and run the install command, and you\'ve got a working marketing platform on your'

[06:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'own box. Or, if you\'ve already got DDEV on your machine, it\'s basically one command, and it wires up the whole environment for you. The current release is Mautic 7, code named Columba, and it landed in January'

[06:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of 2026. The headline edition is projects, a way to group every email, form, and landing page that belongs to one initiative into a single tidy bundle, instead of'

[06:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'everything piling up in one giant flat list. Segment emails got smarter, too. You can now decide whether a send keeps reaching new people as they qualify, or locks to just the audience that existed'

[06:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the moment you hit go. There\'s also clean campaign import and export, so you can build something on a staging site, and move it to production without rebuilding it by hand. And notably, there is no AI feature in here'

[06:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at all, and that absence is the deliberate part. So, who is this actually for? Be honest about the trade-offs first. You are the one running it, which means the server, the updates, and the patches'

[07:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all land on you. And that last one is not theoretical. The most recent release was a security update fixing a whole stack of real vulnerabilities. Deliverability is on you, too. Getting'

[07:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'email reliably into inboxes is a craft that a paid platform quietly handles for you. And the AI layer is still mostly a promise, a set of principles, not a polished assistant you can click today.'

[07:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But, if you\'re a founder or a small team who\'d rather own your stack than lease it, this is about as credible an escape hatch as exists. The interesting part is what happens next, whether a community'

[07:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'writing careful rules can outbuild a dozen venture-backed companies sprinting to weld AI on as fast as they can. Everything\'s linked below if you want to dig in.'
